WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
6.0 English From BBC Learning English.com

2
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBC Learning English, I'm Neil

3
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
And I'm Beth. As a society, we're obsessed with our skin

4
00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:22.000
But the pursuit of perfect skin can make life difficult for people who struggle with skin conditions

5
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:30.000
Sports, Zits or Pimpals. There are many names for the red inflamed marks which appear on the face and neck

6
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:36.000
But the medical term is acne. Acne is a skin condition which can affect anyone

7
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.000
It often happens between the ages of 14 and 19 but can continue into adulthood

8
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:48.000
There are many types of acne from blackheads and whiteheads to more severe forms of cysts and scarring

9
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.000
But whatever the type of acne looking different from others can be emotionally damaging

10
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Especially during the teenage years when our self-image and physical appearance are changing

11
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:06.000
In this program we'll be hearing from a skin doctor or dermatologist who suffered acne herself

12
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And as usual we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary too

13
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:12.000
But first I have a question for you, Beth.

14
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Mild or moderate acne is very common in teenagers and young adults

15
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.000
So according to the UK's National Health Service

16
00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.000
What proportion of people aged 11 to 30 experience some amount of acne?

17
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Is it a 75%

18
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
B 85% or c 95%

19
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Or I'm going to guess that it is c 95%.

20
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Okay Beth will find out if that's the correct answer at the end of the program

21
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.000
Dr. Sharon Crichtschlo is a dermatologist originally from Barbados

22
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:55.000
As someone who grew up with acne she understands the impact it can have on a person's mental health

23
00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:00.000
As she explains here to BBC World Service program the conversation

24
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.000
Well we know for sure that it does stand to arise from puberty onwards

25
00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
So the biggest cohort of patients is in the teenage age group

26
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:16.000
However a proportion of patients up to 20 or so percent certainly in females

27
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.000
It will persist well into the 30s, 40s much longer than people often give it credit for

28
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
And we also know that it has a huge psychological impact

29
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:33.000
So even mild to moderate acne because it affects teenagers who are quite emotionally vulnerable

30
00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:40.000
It affects their friendships, their peer groups and so it should never really be trivialised

31
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:48.000
acne tends to start during puberty the stage in people's lives when they develop from a child into an adult

32
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:50.000
Because of changes in their body

33
00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Hormones such as testosterone which are released into the body during puberty often cause acne to appear

34
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:02.000
Of course puberty involves emotional as well as physical changes

35
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.000
acne can be harder to live with for someone who is emotionally vulnerable

36
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Meaning someone who gets their feelings hurt easily

37
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
acne affects your confidence and how you interact with the world

38
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
So it shouldn't be trivialised or made to seem less important than it really is

39
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
At times most teenagers are self-conscious about their looks

40
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:27.000
And having acne adds to social pressure

41
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:33.000
acne is largely genetic and the buildup of oil and bacteria in the pores of the skin

42
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Which causes spots is due to hormones which are completely natural

43
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Here's Dr. Sharon Crichlow again telling BBC World Service program the conversation

44
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.000
How her own experience with acne led her to help others with the same problem

45
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:53.000
I didn't have the luxury of being able to see a dermatologist when I was younger

46
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
My family simply couldn't afford it so I had to get through it as best I could

47
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:01.000
And you just tried everything over the conctor etc

48
00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:09.000
And I just felt if I could help people with something that has been such a pain of my life

49
00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:13.000
And having that inside experience as well

50
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
So I would often tell my patients pretty much anything I recommend to them

51
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.000
I've tried it myself I can tell them it works

52
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:25.000
Growing up Dr. Crichlow didn't have anyone to help her get through acne

53
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:32.000
If you get through something, you managed to survive a difficult experience or challenging period of life

54
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Instead, she got whatever medicine she could buy without a doctor's prescription

55
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:41.000
Known as over the counter medicines from her local pharmacy

56
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Dr. Crichlow calls acne the bane of my life

57
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:49.000
An idiom meaning the cause of unhappiness or misfortune

58
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:56.000
But as she grew older and her acne improved, she used her experience to support her patients in the UK

59
00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.000
For most people acne stops as they grow older

60
00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:03.000
But remember it's completely natural and you're not alone

61
00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:06.000
Which reminds me of my question, Beth

62
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:10.000
What proportion of 11 to 30 year olds get acne to some extent?

63
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.000
You said it was 95% which was the correct answer

64
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned starting with puberty

65
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
The stage of life when a person changes from a child to an adult

66
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:29.000
Someone who is emotionally vulnerable has their feelings and emotions easily hurt

67
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:34.000
The verb to trivialize means to make something seem less important than it really is

68
00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:40.000
If you get through it, you managed to survive a difficult experience or period of life

69
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:45.000
Over the counter medicines can be bought in a shop without a doctor's prescription

70
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.000
And finally the idiom, the bane of my life

71
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
Refers to a source of persistent unhappiness or misfortune

72
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Once again, our six minutes are up

73
00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:59.000
But remember to join us again next time for more trending topics

74
00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:02.000
And useful vocabulary here at six minutes English

75
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:03.000
Goodbye for now

76
00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Bye

77
